com.ibm.xmi.framework
Interface XMIObject

All Superinterfaces:
Data
All Known Implementing Classes:
XMIObjectImpl
public interface XMIObject
extends Data

This interface represents an XMI object, an instance of a class. XMI objects have values. This interface is named XMIObject to highlight the fact that parts of it are defined by the XMI specification, and to avoid a name conflict with java.lang.Object without requiring you to set up your Java import statements accordingly or use fully qualified names for the classes.

An XMI object in the framework is a subset of OMG MOF and UML instances. It consists of identity properties defined by XMI, and XMI extensions.

You can create XMI objects without creating corresponding XMIClasses in the framework. If an object is an instance of a particular XMIClass, you can set its definer to the class to represent that fact.

XMI objects may have ids, uuids, and labels. An id is a valid XML ID; it must be unique for the objects within an XMI file. A uuid is a globally unique identifier; it must be unique for all objects. Finally, a label is a string that you can use to identify objects; the meaning of the string is not defined by XMI, so you can use it as you wish. The id, uuid, and label are defined in the XMI specification to provide a universal mechanism for identifying objects.

You only need to use the identifiers that you need for your application, and, if your XMI files do not contain cross-file references, you do not need to set any of these identifiers because the framework will automatically assign ids for you when you put your objects in XMI files.

The methods in this class that deal with values allow you to use an XMIObject as a factory for Value objects; you can use the methods of this class to get and set values for objects without creating your own Value objects. You may create your own Value objects and add them to an XMIObject, if you want.

An extension allows you to associate data with objects that is not meant to be shared by other applications. Please see the Extension interface for more details.

To help you create extensions, the framework lets you specify sets of tag values for objects. A tag value is a triple consisting of the name of a set, the name of a tag, and the value for a tag. When an object is written to an XMI file, the tag values for the object are saved in an XMI extension. When an XMI file is loaded, the tag values are restored. Using tag values lets you create an extension for an object without using the Extension interface.

An object may be a proxy for an object in another file; if you use the XMIFiles class to load XMI files, the framework will automatically load XMI files if needed when you attempt to access information about objects. Please see the XMIFiles class documentation for more details.

You may notice that the framework object model does not include behavior for classes or objects; this is a deliberate omission. Only the state of XMI objects is stored in XMI files, not the behavior of the objects. Of course, you can model the behavior of objects in your models if you wish. For example, you can create a model in the framework corresponding to UML, which defines operations and methods for UML classes and UML instances.

addXMIValue

public Value addXMIValue(java.lang.String name,
                         java.lang.Object value)
If there is no Value object with the given name, create one, set its name to the given name and its value to the given value. If there is a Value object with the given name, add the given value to the Value object.

If a new Value is created, its type is set as follows. If the value is java.lang.String, the type of the new Value is set to BASIC. If the value is an XMIObject, the type of the Value is set to REFERENCE.

If you need to create a new Value whose type is ENUM, CONTAINER, or CONTAIN, you need to use void addXMIValue(String name, Object value, int type).

Parameters:
name - The XMI name of the value.
value - The value of the Value object to set or add.
Returns:
The Value object that was created or set.

addXMIValue

public Value addXMIValue(java.lang.String name,
                         java.lang.Object value,
                         int type)
If there is no Value object with the given name, create one, set its name to the given name, its value to the given value, and its type to the given type. If there is a Value object with the given name, add the given value to the Value object. If the given value is a string, and the value of the existing Value object is a string, make the value a collection that contains the two strings. Do a similar thing if the value is XMIObject. If the given value is a Collection and the existing value is a Collection, add each item of the given value to the existing value.
Parameters:
name - The XMI name of the value.
value - The value of the Value object to set or add.
type - The type of the new Value object, if one is created.
Returns:
The Value object that was created or set.

setXMIValue

public Value setXMIValue(java.lang.String name,
                         java.lang.Object value)
If there is a Value object with the given name, set its value to the given value; this value replaces the previous value of the Value object. If there is no Value object with the given name, invoke addXMIValue(name, value).
Parameters:
name - The XMI name of the value.
value - The value of the Value object to set or add.
Returns:
The Value object that was created or had its value set.

setXMIValue

public Value setXMIValue(java.lang.String name,
                         java.lang.Object value,
                         int type)
If there is a Value object with the given name, set its value to the given value; this value replaces the previous value of the Value object. If there is no Value object with the given name, invoke addXMIValue(name, value, type).

If there is already a Value object with the given name, the type parameter is not used.

Parameters:
name - The XMI name of the value.
value - The value of the Value object to set.
type - The type of the Value object to set, if one is created.
Returns:
The Value object created that was created or had its value set.
